            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVIII.R7</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Scene with Ferdinand Barnacle [...]</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-c98abef5-7fff-d013-e946-ed8cb80da336\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although the novel does use the phrase &ldquo;[w]ith this hopeful confession of his faith as the head of the rising Barnacles&rdquo; (LD 718), this note goes much further than many of Dickens&rsquo;s Notes in naming the purpose of a scene. Dickens uses this visit from Barnacle to drive home his points about governmental inadequacy. In this &ldquo;scene,&rdquo; Barnacle acknowledges the &ldquo;humbug&rdquo; of Circumlocution (718), expressing the opinion that &ldquo;nobody cares&rdquo; about inventions (717), and likening the political bureaucracy he represents to &ldquo;a limited game of cricket&rdquo; in which &ldquo;A field of outsiders are always going in to bowl at the Public Service, and we block the balls&rdquo; (716-17).</p>"
        }
